@node "Intro" "Intro"
@prev "main"
@{u}Introduction:@{uu}

    Sepulchre Wood is a @{i}Fighting Fantasy@{ui} - style adventure.  It is 
played in exactly the same way (i.e. Dice, scoresheet, etc.). For the 
rules click @{"here" link "here" 0}.  It is almost essential that a map is made of 
Sepulchre Wood, and landmarks, clearing numbers, etc carefully marked.
@endnode

@node "here" "here"
@prev "Intro"
@{u}Rules:@{uu}
    The first thing you must do is arm yourself with a pen, paper and 
    two dice.  Go on!
        Mark the paper thus -

    Skl | Sta | Luk |          Items         |        Battles
        |     |     |             |
        |     |     |             | Him(St)  Him(St) 
        |     |     |             | -------  -------
        |     |     |             |         
        |     |     |             |               
    Next you must work out your Skill, Stamina and Luck values.
    Roll a die and add 6.  This represents your skill.  Roll
    two dice and add 12 for your stamina, finally roll 1 die and
    add 6 for your luck.  You start with 3 Gold Pieces (You will
    come across others on your travels) and 5 ration packs, which
    restore 4 stamina points each and may be eaten at any time
    in the game.
    @{"Battle" link "battle" 0}
    @{" Luck " link "luck" 0}
@endnode

@node "battle" "battle"
@{u}Battle:@{uu}

    When faced with a creature to slaughter, the text will give you two
    values.  These represent the creatures Skill and Stamina.
    You begin by rolling one die and adding your current Skill.  You 
    repeat the process using the creatures Skill and whoever gets the 
    lowest score loses two stamina points until they be dead! 
    You may face more than one foe, in which case you fight them
    one by one (without stopping for a bite to eat, might I add!).
@endnode

@node "luck" "luck"
@{u}Luck:@{uu}

    From time to time you will be asked to test your luck.  Throw
    both dice.  If the resultant number is higher than your luck, 
    you are unlucky and will probably die!  Each time you test your
    luck, deduct 1 point at the end.  You will be awarded further
    luck points as you play.
    Skill testing is carried out in the same way, but the value remains
    the same unless you are instructed to increase or decrease it.
@endnode
 
@node "info" "info"
@{u}Info:@{uu}

    This game was written in 1993 on paper and Amiga-ised on12 march
1998. Some aspects of the game translated badly to the computer.  Eg, in 
the book I had the Doctor available on call by flipping to a specified page,
but for that to work in Amigaguide, I'd have to have his call number on 
every page - not to mention the obvious pen-and-paper / dice issue.

                @{"Main" link "Main" 0}
